    {
      "num": 1,
      "text": "Which asset misappropriation scheme involves an employee writing a company check to themselves or an accomplice and disguising the disbursement in the accounting records?",
      "tag": "Asset Misappropriation - Fraudulent Disbursements",
      "options": [
        "D. Register disbursement",
        "A. Check tampering",
        "B. Billing scheme",
        "C. Payroll scheme"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "Check tampering occurs when an employee prepares a fraudulent check for their own benefit, either by forging authorization or altering a legitimate check. This is a direct fraudulent disbursement scheme distinct from billing or payroll schemes which involve false documentation. Per CFE Manual, check tampering is unauthorized check preparation or alteration.",
      "justification_wrong": "Billing schemes involve false invoices from shell companies or accomplices. Payroll schemes manipulate employee compensation records. Register disbursements involve direct theft from cash registers at point of sale. These do not specifically involve writing unauthorized company checks to oneself, which defines check tampering per CFE guidelines.",
      "difficulty": "EASY",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "text": "In payroll fraud schemes, which of the following practices does NOT constitute typical fraud?",
      "tag": "Payroll Fraud",
      "options": [
        "A. Inclusion of fictitious employees on the payroll",
        "B. Recording of hours worked exceeding actual hours",
        "C. Artificial inflation of commission rates",
        "D. Payment of salaries below the amount agreed in contract"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "Payroll fraud involves overestimation of compensation—fictitious employees, false hours, and inflated commissions. Paying below the agreed amount is not payroll fraud, but potential breach of contract.",
      "justification_wrong": "Fictitious employees, falsified hours, and inflated commissions are classic modalities of payroll fraud.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_003_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "text": "A fraudster alters the payee name on a company check that has already been signed, making it payable to themselves. This is an example of which scheme?",
      "tag": "Check Tampering",
      "options": [
        "A. Kiting between bank accounts",
        "B. Skimming of cash receipts",
        "C. Check tampering",
        "D. Lapping of accounts receivable"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "Check tampering involves intercepting and modifying a legitimate company check — altering the payee, amount, or other data — for personal gain. (CFE Fraud Examiners Manual 2024)",
      "justification_wrong": "Kiting exploits banking float; skimming is diversion before recording; lapping is covering up receivables deviations — the physical alteration of a check is the defining characteristic of check tampering.",
      "difficulty": "EASY",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_006_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 4,
      "text": "Which internal control failure is the primary one that enables a ghost employee scheme in the payroll?",
      "tag": "Payroll Controls",
      "options": [
        "A. Absence of multi-factor authentication in the HR system",
        "B. Lack of formal documented hiring policy",
        "C. Absence of segregation between approval and payment",
        "D. Absence of independent reconciliation between payroll records and HR files"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "An independent reconciliation would identify employees being paid without corresponding active records in the HR system—a fundamental control to detect ghost employees. (CFE Fraud Examiner Manual)",
      "justification_wrong": "Authentication, hiring policy, and approval/payment segregation are complementary controls—independent reconciliation between payroll and HR is the critical detective control.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_006_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 5,
      "text": "Miranda, a payroll supervisor at a manufacturing company, has been adding fictitious employees to the payroll system for the past eight months. She uses home addresses of vacant properties, creates direct deposit accounts under her control, and ensures the ghost employees are assigned to different departments with varying pay rates. Which of the following controls would be MOST effective in detecting Miranda's ghost employee scheme?",
      "tag": "Ghost Employee",
      "options": [
        "A. Requiring department managers to physically verify and approve the existence of all employees listed on their departmental payroll reports each pay period",
        "B. Implementing a policy that requires all new hire paperwork to include two forms of government-issued identification that are photocopied and maintained in personnel files",
        "C. Establishing a mandate that payroll supervisors take mandatory consecutive vacation days during which another employee assumes all payroll processing responsibilities",
        "D. Configuring the payroll system to flag any employees who share the same bank account information or mailing addresses for management review"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Requiring department managers to physically verify the existence of employees on their payroll reports is the most effective detection control because ghost employees, by definition, never report to work. When managers are required to confirm that each person listed actually works in their department, fictitious employees will be immediately identified since no physical person exists. This independent verification by someone outside the payroll function creates segregation of duties and directly addresses the core vulnerability exploited in ghost employee schemes—the lack of verification that employees actually exist and perform work.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B addresses documentation for new hires but would not detect the scheme because Miranda could fabricate or obtain fraudulent identification documents when creating the ghost employees, and this is a preventive rather than detective control that occurs only at hiring. Option C regarding mandatory vacation is a valuable detective control for many payroll frauds, but Miranda has designed the scheme to appear routine across multiple departments with varying rates, making it less likely that a temporary replacement would immediately recognize the fictitious employees without active verification procedures. Option D would detect some ghost employee schemes where perpetrators reuse bank accounts or addresses, but Miranda has specifically structured her scheme to avoid this red flag by using different vacant property addresses and separate bank accounts, making this control ineffective against her particular approach."
    },
    {
      "num": 6,
      "text": "Sarah, a fraud examiner, is reviewing expense reimbursement claims at a manufacturing company. She notices that Marcus, a sales representative, submitted hotel receipts for a three-day conference in Chicago. The receipts show he stayed at a premium hotel for $450 per night. Sarah's investigation reveals that Marcus actually stayed at a budget hotel for $120 per night and altered the original receipts by manipulating the amounts and hotel name using photo editing software. Marcus received reimbursement for the inflated amounts. What type of expense reimbursement scheme has Marcus committed?",
      "tag": "Expense Reimbursement",
      "options": [
        "A. Mischaracterized expense reimbursement scheme",
        "B. Overstated expense reimbursement scheme",
        "C. Fictitious expense reimbursement scheme",
        "D. Multiple reimbursement scheme"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "This is an overstated expense reimbursement scheme because Marcus actually incurred a legitimate business expense (the hotel stay) but manipulated the supporting documentation to inflate the actual cost from $120 to $450 per night. In overstated schemes, the employee genuinely incurs the expense but seeks reimbursement for an amount greater than what was actually paid by altering receipts or other supporting documents. The key characteristic is that a real expense occurred, but the perpetrator misrepresents the true amount to obtain excess reimbursement.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option A is incorrect because a mischaracterized expense scheme involves claiming a personal expense as a business expense, such as submitting a personal dinner receipt as a client entertainment expense. Marcus's hotel stay was legitimately business-related for the conference. Option C is incorrect because a fictitious expense scheme involves submitting claims for expenses that never occurred at all, such as creating fake receipts for nonexistent purchases. Marcus did actually stay at a hotel and incurred real lodging expenses. Option D is incorrect because a multiple reimbursement scheme involves seeking payment more than once for the same expense, such as submitting the same receipt to different managers or combining company reimbursement with client billing for the same cost. Marcus only submitted the altered receipts once for reimbursement."
    },
    {
      "num": 7,
      "text": "Maria, a payroll supervisor at a manufacturing company, has been adding fictitious employees to the payroll system for the past 18 months. She creates fake personnel files, processes direct deposits to accounts she controls, and ensures these ghost employees are assigned to different departments with varying supervisors. Which of the following internal controls would be MOST effective in detecting Maria's ghost employee scheme?",
      "tag": "Ghost Employee",
      "options": [
        "A. Requiring the human resources department to independently verify all employees on the payroll register against active personnel files each quarter",
        "B. Implementing a policy that all new hires must complete Form I-9 within three days of their start date and submit it to the compliance office",
        "C. Mandating that all payroll disbursements exceeding $5,000 per pay period require dual authorization from the payroll manager and controller",
        "D. Establishing a requirement that department supervisors review and approve timesheets electronically before payroll processing each pay period"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Independent verification by HR against the payroll register is the most effective control because it directly addresses the ghost employee scheme by comparing two independent sources of data. This reconciliation would identify employees appearing on payroll who lack corresponding legitimate personnel files, exposing the fictitious workers. The independence of the HR function from payroll processing is critical, as it creates segregation of duties that prevents a payroll supervisor from both creating false records and verifying them. This periodic reconciliation specifically targets the vulnerability Maria exploited by creating both payroll entries and fake personnel files.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B is incorrect because while Form I-9 compliance is important for employment eligibility verification, Maria already created fake personnel files, which could easily include fraudulent I-9 forms. This control focuses on immigration compliance rather than detecting fictitious employees after they've been added to the system. Option C is incorrect because the dollar threshold applies to individual disbursements, not cumulative payments to ghost employees. Maria's scheme likely involves multiple smaller payments to different fictitious employees that individually fall below the $5,000 threshold, allowing the fraud to bypass this control entirely. Option D is incorrect because timesheet approval by supervisors assumes the employees actually exist and are assigned to specific departments. Since Maria assigned ghost employees across different departments, supervisors unfamiliar with all workers in their areas might approve timesheets without recognizing the employees are fictitious, especially in larger departments with high turnover or shift work."
    },
    {
      "num": 8,
      "text": "Rachel Martinez, a payroll manager at a regional manufacturing company, has been processing paychecks for an employee named \"David Chen\" for the past 18 months. During a routine internal audit, the fraud examiner discovers that David Chen's personnel file contains only minimal documentation, his time cards are always approved by Rachel, and his paychecks are direct-deposited to an account that Rachel has signature authority over. David Chen has never participated in the company's health insurance program, and no other employees recall meeting him. Which of the following analytical procedures would MOST effectively detect this type of scheme on an ongoing basis?",
      "tag": "Ghost Employee",
      "options": [
        "A. Comparing the payroll register against human resources records and independently verifying employees with department managers who lack payroll responsibilities",
        "B. Reconciling total payroll expenditures to the prior year's amounts and investigating any increases that exceed the inflation rate by more than two percentage points",
        "C. Requiring all employees to use biometric time clocks and reviewing exception reports for employees who consistently clock in at the same time each pay period",
        "D. Conducting random audits of personnel files to ensure that all required tax forms and employment eligibility documentation have been properly completed and retained"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Option A is the most effective control because ghost employee schemes succeed when payroll records are not independently verified against actual personnel. By comparing payroll registers to HR records and obtaining independent confirmation from department managers who have no payroll access or authority, the organization creates segregation of duties and independent verification. Department managers would be able to confirm whether employees actually work in their areas, and this cross-reference would immediately identify discrepancies where someone appears on payroll but is unknown to operational managers. This procedure directly addresses the core vulnerability in ghost employee fraud: the ability of a payroll insider to add fictitious employees without detection through independent verification channels.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B is insufficient because year-over-year payroll comparisons are too broad to detect individual ghost employees, especially when the scheme involves relatively small amounts or when legitimate hiring, raises, or overtime can mask the fraudulent additions. A single ghost employee's salary might fall within normal variance ranges. Option C focuses on time clock manipulation but would not detect a ghost employee scheme where the perpetrator simply fabricates time records or sets consistent patterns to avoid suspicion; biometric systems only verify that someone clocked in, not that the employee is legitimate. Option D addresses documentation compliance but does not verify that employees actually exist or work at the company; a sophisticated perpetrator like Rachel could easily create complete personnel files with forged documents for the ghost employee, making this control ineffective for detection."
    },
    {
      "num": 9,
      "text": "Maria, an accounts payable clerk at a manufacturing company, notices that sales representative Jason has submitted expense reports for the same business dinner on three separate occasions over a six-month period. Each report shows identical dates, restaurant names, and amounts ($287.50), but lists different client names as attendees. The company's expense reimbursement policy requires supporting documentation only for expenses exceeding $500. What is Maria's MOST appropriate initial action to address this potential fraud indicator?",
      "tag": "Expense Reimbursement",
      "options": [
        "A. Request that Jason provide original receipts and verification of the client meetings for all three expense submissions to determine if duplicate reimbursements occurred.",
        "B. Immediately report Jason to law enforcement authorities since the pattern of identical amounts constitutes prima facie evidence of expense reimbursement fraud.",
        "C. Deny only the most recent expense submission and approve the earlier two claims since they have already been processed through the normal approval workflow.",
        "D. Conduct a covert investigation by accessing Jason's email and calendar without his knowledge to verify whether the client meetings actually occurred."
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Option A represents the appropriate initial response to a red flag in expense reimbursement. When duplicate or suspicious expenses are identified, the first step is to gather additional documentation and verify the legitimacy of the claims before making accusations. Requesting original receipts and meeting verification allows Maria to determine whether this is an innocent error (such as resubmitting a rejected claim) or intentional fraud involving mischaracterized or fictitious expenses. This approach follows proper internal control procedures by seeking clarification before escalation, while also creating a documented audit trail. Under expense reimbursement fraud examination protocols, verification of supporting documentation is the foundation for determining whether duplicate reimbursements or fictitious expense schemes have occurred.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B is premature and excessive. While identical amounts and dates are fraud indicators, they do not constitute prima facie evidence requiring immediate law enforcement involvement. The appropriate chain of response involves internal verification first, then reporting through proper organizational channels (such as to management or internal audit) before involving external authorities. Option C is inappropriate because it fails to address the underlying issue and potentially allows fraudulent reimbursements to stand. Simply denying the latest claim while approving potentially fraudulent earlier claims does not fulfill fiduciary responsibilities or internal control objectives. Option D violates privacy rights and potentially breaks federal laws such as the Stored Communications Act. Accessing an employee's email and calendar without proper authorization, legal grounds, or the employee's knowledge constitutes an inappropriate investigative technique that could expose the company to legal liability and render any evidence inadmissible."
    },
    {
      "num": 10,
      "text": "Sarah Chen, a payroll manager at a manufacturing company, has been processing paychecks for an employee named Michael Torres for the past 18 months. Torres appears on all payroll reports and receives direct deposits biweekly. However, during a routine audit, the fraud examiner discovers that Torres has never clocked in, has no employee file in human resources, and his listed Social Security number belongs to Sarah's husband. The direct deposits go to an account that Sarah can access. Which element most directly establishes this scheme as ghost employee fraud rather than another form of payroll fraud?",
      "tag": "Ghost Employee",
      "options": [
        "A. Torres is a fictitious person who does not actually perform any work for the company but receives compensation through the payroll system",
        "B. Sarah has the ability to manipulate payroll records and redirect funds to accounts under her control",
        "C. The fraud has continued for an extended period without detection by management or internal controls",
        "D. Torres appears in the payroll system with fraudulent identification information including a misappropriated Social Security number"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "The defining characteristic of ghost employee fraud is that the 'employee' does not exist or does not work for the organization, yet receives compensation through the payroll system. The essence of this scheme is the creation of a phantom worker on the payroll who performs no actual services. The fact that Torres never clocks in, has no HR file, and does not actually work for the company while receiving regular paychecks establishes this as a ghost employee scheme. The perpetrator creates or maintains a fictitious person on the payroll to misappropriate funds, which distinguishes it from other payroll frauds involving real employees.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B describes a control weakness and method of execution that could apply to multiple types of payroll fraud schemes, including falsified hours, commission schemes, or unauthorized raises for real employees—not specifically ghost employee fraud. Option C identifies a duration factor and control deficiency common to many fraud schemes across categories, but does not distinguish ghost employee fraud from other payroll manipulations that could also persist undetected. Option D focuses on the use of false identification, which is a mechanism used to facilitate the scheme, but fraudulent credentials could also be used in identity theft scenarios or to conceal other payroll frauds; the critical element is the nonexistence of the worker performing services, not merely the falsification of documents."
    },
